summary:
Japan's Cabinet approved guidelines ending the postwar ban on lethal weapons exports. The policy shift enables sales of fighter jets and drones amid threats from China and North Korea. Japan's arms industry receives a boost, and defense spending increases. Global arms trade expands as a result.

In eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran Congolese troops using gunfire and shelling before entering Goma city, a safe-haven for over one million displaced residents. Civilians and aid operations face disruptions; evacuation efforts continue. Separately, displaced Palestinians crossed a military zone on foot into northern Gaza after Israel broke a hostage deal deadlock. Hundreds of thousands return amid reconstruction challenges. In Ukraine, armed unmanned ground vehicles carrying bombs and guns deployed for attacks to address ground troop shortages. Frontline soldiers avoid risks; Russia positions targeted.

China's nuclear association reported capacity to build 50 reactors simultaneously across full project cycles. The energy sector advances clean power; China positions for nuclear technology exports. Developer Vanke reported massive losses, widening the real estate crisis. Homebuyers, investors, and the economy affected; state intervention considered. A federal judge sentenced Purdue Pharma to forfeit $225 million to the Justice Department, resolving opioid charges and enabling settlements in thousands of lawsuits. Victims and states receive funds. A gunman killed one Canadian and wounded 13 tourists atop Teotihuacan pyramids in Mexico; authorities investigate motive. Three Japan Ground Self-Defense Force members died in a tank explosion during training at Hijudai maneuver area in Oita Prefecture; investigation underway."}
